Ask HN: How are you teaching local/online courses?
text:
For anyone who's:

- Teaching local courses for their community, at their own imperative, either volunteer or paid / profitable, or

- Teaching online courses out of personal interest, or

- Providing other training...

I'm interested in knowing:

- What do you teach, and how's it going?

- Are you in-person, online, or both? What tools do you use?

- How do you announce your courses / availability?

- Are you accepting payment / donations and how's that working out for you?

- Anything else you can share?

Background: I can probably set aside some time for, and have some interest in teaching community courses. I've done this in the past in various ways, but this was years ago.

I'm thinking of some simple topics that have been relevant in my community in the past, like intro to AM/FM/Shortwave radio for emergencies, or let's say how to enjoy geocaching. I could get into some more high-demand general topics but want to start simple.

I previously taught these kinds of courses as part of a service framework in a religion I was a member of at the time. But now that's changed, and I'll need to manage the outreach, venue scouting, and scheduling more directly by myself.

So, some parts of this seem a bit foreign to me, not having a huge organization at my back anymore. Also I realize things are different since COVID.

Thanks for any tips and experiences you can share.

Ask HN: Do you have a separate home and work desk?
text:
I have a hybrid remote work setup where I'm in the office three days a week. It's a short drive so I don't mind the commute. At home I have one desk and one monitor used by my work laptops (yes plural) and my personal desktop. Peripherals are shared via a cheap USB 3 switch.

It makes for a messy desk. I've been thinking about splitting my work/home setup and was curious if anyone else has done the same. If so, did it work well for you? Was it worth the investment to make two working areas?

My father-in-law Instagram account was hacked, how can we get it back?
text:
My father-in-law have a small business of paellas which he uses to support his family. He have an instagram account called @paellasantamarta which he uses to get most of his customers.

Two days ago some criminal sent a link pretending to be Instagram official account with a phishing link. He was naive and put the account information there.

Soon after some US mobile (+1 XXX) told they hacked his account and want some ransom to return it.

He got some mails indicating that the email was changed and password. The account is now deactivate.

- We tried to undo the change but it's not possible with the instagram emails nor the past login information - We tried to recover multiple times the account via the face verification but he always get this message: "We weren't able to confirm your identity from the video you submitted. You can submit a new video and we'll review it again. Learn more."

Is there something else we can try? We thought about paying the hacker (the ransom is quite hefty for him) but no one assures that we will get the account back.

He is desperate and nervous, he barely slept in the last two days because he is going to lose his small business of paellas. We warned about the phishing attacks but he is stubborn and was convinced Instagram was going to close is account.

Show HN: SayThisInstead – An A.I. based tool for saying things professionally
text:
Hi HN!

Introducing saythisinstead - a communication tool that helps you say things more gracefully at work. It is currently in public beta, and I would love for you to try it out.

You can ask saythisinstead to help you communicate more professionally, and it provides a simple input/output interface and it is free to try. Additionally, you can view your previous questions and get inspiration from the "popular answers" section.

The technology behind saythisinstead is based on ChatGPT, but it provides much better and more precise answers in the context of work communication. I have also included a quick video for a side-by-side comparison on the landing page.

Would love to hear your feedback!
